Oct 28 2009 	Mostly good...	I stayed at this hotel for 4 days in Oct. (it was my first trip to Beijing) and was pleased with the swift check-in and the room was to my liking. I thought the all-glass bathroom was kind of unique and because I was travelling by myself, it didn't bother me one bit! Other positives included the fact that it was very close to Tian'anmen Square, the Forbidden City, and the night food market (You MUST try the dumplings at the market! I currently live in Asia and these are the best I've ever had - hands down!). It was also close to convenience stores and a moderate distance from a great little restaurant called Grandma's Kitchen on Beichizi St. As you head left out of the hotel, Beichizi St. is the first street you come to. Turn left and the restaurant is on the right-hand side of the street, maybe 2-3 min. walk from the corner where you turned (about a 7-10 min. walk from hotel)....the restaurant blends into the other buildings there, so if you aren't looking, you may miss it! It has a variety of foods (Western and Asian) that have great flavor and the prices are VERY reasonable! I highly recommend it!!A slight negative about the hotel was the 15 min. walk to the subway, but I expected that having read previous reviews, and the upside was that I discovered the aforementioned resturant! Another relatively-minor negative was the fact that when the maid cleaned the room, she neglected to replace the toilet paper (i.e., there was none in the bathroom at all! Not even a spare roll, which you usually find in many other hotels, even in Asia!)...which is annoying by itself, but even moreso when I had to call down to get some brought to my room and then had to go downstairs to make the request again because it hadn't come after about 10-15 min. of waiting. A more frustrating negative was the difficulty I had one evening trying to get a cab to go to a resturant that was recommended to me by a fellow traveller. My attempts to get help from the hotel receptionist and concierge were pointless, as in the end, they tried to figure out where I wanted to go (even though it was written in pinyang(sp?)) and attempted to flag down no less than 6 cabs and explain where I wanted to go with no success. At that point, I was so annoyed that I decided to just do something different for dinner...but that whole situation could have been a function of the obscurity of where I wanted to go?? Not sure...A more pressing negative was the fact that the phone in my room stopped working on my 2nd day there, which I normally wouldn't care about; However, I was waiting for a phone call, so when I returned from a long day of touring and the message indicator light wasn't on, I naturally attempted to make a call the front desk about it, which was how I discovered it wasn't working. When I went down to report that I thought my phone might be faulty and that I was concerned because I was expecting a phone call from my tour guide for the next day, they did not indicate that they were aware of the problem, nor did they indicate that he had called. It was only 5-10 min. later when one of the bellmen came up to my room to give me a handwritten message that it was evident that they knew about the phone problem! In fact, when I returned the tour guide's call, he said that he had called 10 times (literally!) and when the hotel person finally told him that there was a problem with my phone, he asked that a message be hand-delivered to me in person. When I asked him what time this transpired, he said it was 2-3 hours prior! Needless to say, he was extremely annoyed and frustrated, as was I! My frustration was intensified when I tried to explain the problem to the front desk person and got NO WHERE! Anyway, I didn't let that color the rest of my trip - I truly enjoyed the rest of the aspects of my stay in Beijing and I would still recommend this hotel.	
