Jul 2 2009 	Stylish hotel great location wonderful price!	I just completed a stay at Hotel Kapok and I cannot say enough good things, especially in comparison with some of the more grotty Chinese hotels in which I had stayed on this trip. Modern, interesting architecture, great location, good English from the staff, and very friendly service. Plus the price is right! I got a great deal on the internet, especially compared with hotels on Wangfujing just a few blocks away.The breakfast buffet was very good with choices for American, European, Japanese and Chinese tastes. Even smoked salmon, my way of judging hotel breakfasts, plus ground to order coffee as well as made to order eggs. I didn’t eat dinner at the hotel, preferring the range of Chinese restaurants right on the street. I also went twice to the massage place nearby, one of the nicest I have visited outside of a fancy spa. For sightseeing, the proximity to the Forbidden City and other famous places is great.Who should not stay at Hotel Kapok? If you need a full range of business services, this is not the place. There was free internet connection in the room that worked perfectly. I needed to print something from the internet and the small business center could handle that, but didn’t look like they could do much more.Similarly, if you need concierge service for sightseeing, transportation, and the like, I don’t think the staff can handle very much. Getting taxis—no problem. Arranging for a tour could be a challenge.I liked the emphasis on glass throughout the hotel, but some people might freak out at the glass walls around the bathroom. If you or your roommate might be embarrassed by showering in full view, you can pull the curtains but then much of the charm is gone.The hotel is new and fairly small so taxi drivers don’t know it. The name in Chinese is mu mian hua but even that doesn’t help a lot. Once you check into the hotel you will have a card with a map and the address although some drivers still seemed perplexed. Before leaving home, I carefully copied the name of the hotel off the website, and wrote the address in Chinese characters so I had something to give to the taxi driver at the airport. Otherwise it would have been difficult to get there. I wish the hotel would give this information on its website so prospective guests could print it out when making reservations.I will definitely stay there on my next Beijing trip!	
Jun 20 2009 	Fab location neat hotel with reasonable rates	We arrived 7 am in the morning, and even we had not informed them in advance, two rooms were provided immediately without a question. Also, when we left, we were allowed to keep the room for couple extra hours (3 hours).Don't be put-off by the facade, it is a little dull, but inside is totally different. The rooms were nicely decorated, new and clean. Some fruits and drinking water was also provided. The breakfast wasn't impressive, but as it was included to the rate (about 800 CNY/night for double room), it was enough to keep us going for some hours. And we kept going: Tian An Men Square, Forbidden City, Walking / shopping street, Royal Palace are all within walking distance. In the evening a night market opens up 200 meters from the hotel, on the same street. I would, and likely will, go back to Kapok Hotel, if rates remain reasonable. Now, I know you can get a room with much less than 300 CNY from almost any city in China. But I want to enjoy my vacation, and for that (or, for business trip, they also provide free internet) this was a good choice.	
Jun 14 2009 	Fantastic Hotel!	We really loved this unique hotel! Once again tripadvisor proved very reliable because I booked this hotel on the basis of recommendations and its amazing value for money. We stayed for 5 nights after decamping from our conference hotel further out of the city. The hotel's website makes the Kapok look a little minimalist and cool, but in fact it has a very warm vibe with some nice, quirky touches. The rooms are light, warm and pleasant and the courtyards make a big difference. Staff were very friendly and helpful and spoke pretty good English. Free internet access from your room was a plus. There's also an excellent restaurant across the road from the hotel, although the hotel has a restaurant, there's so many good ones within walking distance.As others have noted, the location's great. I'd defininitely stay here again and recommend it highly.	
Jun 11 2009 	Gorgeous hotel perfect location for tourists	I booked this hotel based on Trip Advisor reviews, as it was rated amongst much more expensive hotels, and was impressed with everything from the moment I arrived. All the staff I encountered spoke English well, the reception and bar area were modern and welcoming and the rooms...gorgeous. I had a courtyard room and although the courtyard was facing into the hotel corridor and not outside it was such a pretty addition to the room and different to anything I've ever seen before.The room was spacious and very clean, the mini bar was well stocked and the room service menu had a decent selection of reasonably priced Western and Chinese dishes. I ate room service a couple of times and the food was on a par with anything I've had from room service in European 5* hotels. The glass bathroom walls added to the feeling of spaciousness (great for a lone traveller, there are curtains if you have company) and a good selection of toiletries - toothbrush, shaving kit, comb, the usual soapy things. The TV wasn't showing any English language channels due to a fault but I wasn't in Beijing to watch television. The bed was firm bordering on hard the way all beds in Chinese hotels seem to be and my view was onto the back of some apartments. Not an issue for me as I didn't spend much time looking out of the window. You can order a selection of pillows to be brought to your room which is a nice idea, although I was fine with the ones already there.The location of the hotel is as good as you could ask for as a tourist new to Beijing. The Forbidden City and Tiananmen Square were both 5 minutes walk away and Wangfujing was 2 minutes walk in the opposite direction. Over the road is a Subway and there are plenty of Western chains in Wangfujing. Lots of shops to stock up on wine, beer and snacks nearby as the mini bar isn't particularly cheap. Beware of local tour guidestouting for business if you're new to Beijing. I thought 'why not?' and paid one to go round the Forbidden City, but I was whisked round in about 90 minutes when other people have said they spent several hours there. On the other hand I had also pre-booked a personal guide for a day via Expedia and this was excellent - I had a limited amount of time and he was able to help me see lots in one day because he knew the ropes when it came to getting in places - at the Olympic sites for example you buy a ticket at one place and the entrance is elsewhere. I'd recommend this for anyone passing through and wanting to pack in as much sight seeing as possible. £60ish for 8 hours and they can hold the things you're not allowed to take through the Mao mausoleum and know where is nearby and what is open when to get best use of your time. If you do one thing while you're in Beijing, it's get as far away as possible and get on an unrestored part of the Great Wall. I hiked between Jinshanling and Simatai and was blown away by it. You need to be quite fit to do it and wear trainers because the terrain is very steep and at times rubbly but you will be completely immersed in the wall and start to understand what a feat it was to build it. This part was very quiet too, just our tour group. I'm almost reluctant to post this part because it's so unspoiled it seems a shame to encourage more people to go.	
