Apr 18 2009 	Perfect in every way!	We stayed there for 4 nights, and I did not want to leave. This is a 5-star luxury accomodation at dirt-cheap rates, within 2 minutes walking from the East gate (Donghuamen) of the Forbidden City, 5 minute walk of Wangfujing St., and 10-15 minute walk to the subway (either Wangfujing, or Tian'anmendong stations). However: their advertised rate is much higher than what we paid. We've been told that one negotiates prices in China - barring that, one books via online sites, which generally have the highest discounts. We found this to be absolutely true. When we called the hotel and asked for the cheapest room (Fashion Room), we were told none was available, and the next higher (Courtyard Room) was 880 yuan/night. We then went online at elong.net (NB: this is a Chinese website, with English interface, which gets much better rates within China than expedia, priceline etc.) and found that the Fashion Room WAS available, for 518 yuan/night, and the Courtyard was 780 yuan/night. We booked the cheapest - without providing any credit card information, just a name and email, and got back the confirmation within minutes. The hotel received this reservation without problem, honored the quoted rate, and upgraded us for free to a Courtyard. I have no idea what the Fashion Room looks like, but the Courtyard is unbelievable. You have a small pebble/flower garden inside your room, futuristic looking temperature and light controls, every conceivable amenity in the bathroom and bar (let me just say: 2 sets of flip-flops, one for the bedroom, one for the bath), complimentary fruit basket upon arrival, prompt and unobtrusive daily service (and no stinting on shower supplies, either). The room is big, the bathroom is huge (shower-only, though). I want such a bathroom for my own house! Internet: Kapok has free internet (via Ethernet cable) in the room, and free wireless on the first floor (also available from parts of our 2nd fl. room). We did not have a laptop, but we had a WiFi smart phone, which proved quite useful. If you have neither, you can pay rip-off prices for access to a computer in their business center. As an aside, there's also a library on the 1st floor, with some English books you can check out.The staff at Kapok speaks fluent English, right down to the bellhop. They were infallibly attentive and polite - but unlike most Chinese places, they do expect tips. Breakfast was not included in our discount rate, but we could see the restaurant through large windows, and it looked fully stocked with all the Continental staples. We could have bought breakfast for 80 yuan/person, but opted not to. There's a Subway restaurant just across the street (good luck explaining the concept of &quot;black coffee&quot; to them, though!)	
Apr 18 2009 	Loved the hotel hated the city	Hooray for Hotel Kapok, an oasis in Beijing. Location is great, central but just that little bit off the beaten track and in an area which feels authentically Chinese (unlike in the area just down the road full of the plush hotels which could be anywhere). Three good restaurants a stone's throw away - one next door in a hotel (out the door, turn right), buffet lunch for 68Y each including drinks. Cantonese restaurant with great Peking Duck, out of the door, turn left, on the corner with big flashing sign. And by the Forbidden City, have a budget blow out at The Courtyard, although that's more Western fusion.Hotel staff very friendly and helpful, some speak very good English (especially the bellboy). Room great - we had a garden room on the 2nd floor. The bathroom wall is all glass, so go with a very good friend. Or you'll be good friends afterwards for sure! The bed is the hardest I have ever slept on but it wasn't an issue. A bit of noise from the neighbouring rooms - we could hear upstairs showering and next door in the throes of passion.... well at least someone's getting some. There's free cabled internet and a LCD TV, plus fridge and mini bar. They charge Western prices though - a beer is £2.50 when you can buy them in the supermarket 2 roads down for 39p. Also there's a charge for tea and coffee, plus one of those nasty fake milk sachets is 40p - that's a bit tight, but then everyone wants your cash in Beijing. Do what we did and help yourself to some extra teabags at breakfast time. And some milk. One up for us - ha. Breakfast is extensive but somehow misses the mark.Very glad we stayed here. It proved a comfortable oasis in a city we couldn't wait to leave. So if you really must come to Beijing, at least stay here!	
