Dec 2 2008 	The first hotel I've ever stayed in that I couldn't actually fault	The Kapok is a stunning little hotel right in the centre of Beijing, around 10 minutes walk from the Forbidden City of Wangfujing Street. The nearest subway station is a good 15-20 minute walk away, but taxi's are plentiful and very very cheap.From the outside it's probably best described as 'interesting' but, once inside, it's a lovely hotel. The staff are ever present and helpful - there's probably too many, but having so many people helping you as you go in and out of the hotel each day is a pleasure.The room (our was a Courtyard Room, a small upgrade) was spacious and beautifully designed. On entering there's a corridor to the main room, which is a mix of dark woods and bright white light, with a large bed and plenty of floor space. Enough storage, a large TV and an enormous mini-bar finished off the living area, while a stunning glass walled bathroom added a bit of glamour. Curtains are in place to wrap around the bathroom for those times a bit of privacy is needed. At the front of the room, and despite being on the fifth floor, we had our own garden, complete with table and chairs. Really.The bar area was again a light and spacious area, although perhaps a little expensive. That said, hotel bars are never cheap. I didn't use the restaurant, but having poked my head round the door, it looked suitably high quality - I have to assume the food matched the surroundings, but that may not be the case. In the basement is a fitness room and a tourist sales office. The latter was extremely helpful, managing to acquire, through means I didn't investigate too thoroughly, some overnight sleeper tickets that had sold out when we checked elsewhere. A small fee is charged, but nothing that would put you off. This is also where the internet PC's are, and they offered pretty good value for money.For the price (around £85 a night), it's one of the best hotels I've stayed in, and proved to be a valuable respite from the non-stop activity of Beijing.Highly recommended.	
Nov 19 2008 	Overall Very Good	Very nice, boutique style hotel. Reserved in advance thru the hotel booking agent in the US. Since everything is negotiable, in China, the request we made was to have breakfast included in the price and to upgrade room if possible. The agent assured me she would take care of it. Check in was easy but they only set-up one breakfast in the cost and no mention in the agents notes about the possible upgrade.The person on the desk was very nice and arranged for 2 breakfasts and for 8,00 per night we upgraded to a Garden Room. The garden room was attached to a 10 x 15 foot beautiful garden with bamboo and table and chairs (well worth it). We looked at the suites and they were magnificent.The lobby and breakfast room was clean and well staffed. The food was plenty, Chinese and American style. Plenty of good choices, good coffee, etc.The location was a 5 minute walk to the Forbidden City. Not the greatest area but no problems, even at 3:00 AM.Close to the snack street and easy to get around with taxis - the metro stop wasn't close/The room was beautiful. The bathroom was all glass walls with a floor to ceiling pull curtain. Everything was clean and serviced daily. Plenty of storage in modern upstyle build-ins.The staff spoke very good English and helped with tours to the Great Wall and directions anywhere. Make sure you have the hotel card- taxi drivers did not speak English.Only bad taste was on check-ou they tried to charge us for 3 washcloths my wife used to take off her make-up. They said they could not get them cleaned but I refused to pay for them. They dropped it.Overall, good location, clean hotel, good staff, fair price. Paid 153.00 per night for Garden Room with 2 breakfasts (including all service fees)	
Nov 4 2008	5 nights stay-superb deal  very close but also very isolated lousy breakfast	I booked the room through Splendia.com for about $112/nts in Last April '08 and it was the cheapest without sacrificing the quality. But there are areas you can definitely will notice it cannot be compared to 5 star hotels.Initially, the night crew tried to check me into a very small cornered room, insisting that is the deluxe. Well, it wasn't and I insisted I couldn't stay there and the pics from my reservation were not the same. All of sudden, although it was fully booked in the hotel, one deluxe room was released and I could check into the better rooms that you can see in the pics other reviewers provided here. But it gave me a wrong idea. There was nothing you can do around that area at night-after 11pm. And, we walked around the little hutong around the Forbidden city wall. That was most memorable 2 hours of walk.Then we had a very late dinner across the hotel. This was a very small eatery where the humble locals hang out after finishing days hard works, The owner was a very handsome guy with great smiles to us, and he chose 4 dishes for two of us. And, it was most delicious meal I had for the entire 2 week stay in China. And, the food only cost us $13 with drinks. Unfortunately I did not know how to pronounce the name but it was next to the mart/convenient store across the hotel and it is open till 3-4am. Well, the location is great, at first, as you can walk easily to Tienanmen Square-20-30min., Yes, it is like walking in Moscow and things are really far stretched out but you could almost sea the east gate to the city wall. Very grand. But, at night, it is frustrating as the bicyclists approach you to trade something all along, or, even the bell boys cannot find taxi and we had to walk to the main street. The street itself is very dark but it is just like anywhere in beiing and I rather like it. There is no threat with the locals and you will feel safe anywhere.The bed was great, and the gas mask in the room was a bit funny. The shower glass booth is the excellent gesture with the curtain surrounds. The view to the outside is a wall and you would not want to peek out as it is a drab neighboring building just across a narrow alley.The breakfast room is still nicely located but I would not even compare it to that of Holiday or Ramada Inn in USA at $10. But, there is no other option around the hotel for the morning really. When we went to Silk Market and other new developmed area with CCTV, I found bigger hotels with Western Scale Boulavards but I thought the choice we made was still good and it was a definitely different experience as we actually stayed on/in the hutong, the old neighbors along the castle walls. That made the Kapok special. But, the taxi driver did not know the name even with the fully printed address in Chinese. So, that is the minus. If you like a good deal, you will be pleasantly surprised with the room decor and its size. And, If you like to hit two great walls locations in one day, hire a taxi driver for a day- $130 +$20 tip including a 1 hour drive over the olympic sites. it took us 12 hours and it was worth it for two.The hotel staff, Zhao Yao and Andy Liu speak decent English and their help outshined the minor incconveniences. They were really helpful., And, they wouldn''t take my tips initially on the check out day. But, in the street, the ordinary Beijing people are not that cool, but they are definitely peaceful and I find them more charming than Shanhai people. I hope they stay the same when i return someday.	
Oct 25 2008 	Great location	The Hotel Kapok is in a great location in central Beijing. It is a short walk from the Forbidden City and Tiananmen Square. Further down the road it is in is the city's night food market - complete with deep fried silk worms and crickets. It is also near the Wangfujing shopping area.We paid for the cheapest-rate courtyard room but on arrival were upgraded to a suite. This was fantastic - spacious, huge bath, and included a computer with free internet access.The only niggles are the services. We booked a private trip to the great wall through the hotel's travel booking service, which was very poor. Room service always came with mistakes (the staff answering the phone didn't speak much English). The restaurant's breakfast buffet had a lot of choice but the food wasn't great quality e.g. stale, hard pastries and muffins.But on the whole I would heartily recommend this hotel because of it's great location and nice rooms.	
