Aug 22 2008 	Avoid the Kapok Hotel!! Terrible customer service!	We stayed at the Hotel Kapok in Beijing for 11 nights during the Olympic Games in August 2008 as part of our honeymoon. We had pre-booked the accommodation (a Courtyard room) about 9 months in advance using asiahotels.com/hotelclub.net and had a pre-paid voucher for the entire stay with us.We arrived after a long 15 hour trip and presented the voucher to the front desk manager. After examining the voucher for about 20 minutes due to a lack of English language capabilities we were informed that the hotel would not be honouring the voucher since the rates that we had paid were &quot;too cheap since it was the Olympics&quot;. Apparently we would be able to stay in the hotel for 2 nights only before needing to move out. We explained that we had pre-paid and booked the accommodation in advance and the fact that the hotel had agreed to the rates then meant that we had a valid contract to stay at the prices we had paid. The front desk manager checked us in for 2 days saying she would try and extend our stay.At this point we contact Hotelclub.net in Australia and requested them to sort out the issue and they said they would follow up on this. Approximately two hours later we receive a call from the front desk saying we will need to move out of the hotel since Government officials had booked all the rooms and we would not be able to stay in the hotel. Again we informed Hotelclub about this. Over the course of the next 2 days we were hassled by the hotel staff to the extent that they sent porters to our door to try and remove our luggage from our room, whilst Hotelclub was very ineffective in resolving the problem. Their resolution consisted of trying to move us to a lower grade hotel which we rejected or to a sister hotel of the Kapok that no one had heard of. Both of these options were not satisfactory to us. As far as we were concerned the issue was between Hotel Kapok and Hotelclub to sort out as regards rates/bookings etc. we had a valid confirmation voucher and were now being evicted from our room.In the end Hotel Kapok &quot;managed&quot; to find us another room where we could stay which was of a lower standard then we had booked (a regular room vs. a courtyard room) and did not have any windows, only a roof light. Moreover, the bathroom is surrounded by clear glass and unlike the courtyard room which has a curtain to surround the bathroom, our second room did not have this and was clearly meant for single occupancy only. To add insult to injury throughout the time we were there, we did not see a single Government official and the only other occupants we saw were Western tourists. Cleaning staff also confirmed that the rooms were empty and there was no reason for all the problems we had experienced that wasted 2 days of our honeymoon and ruined the start of our Beijing visit.No apologies, explanations etc. have followed from either Hotel Kapok or Hotelclub. In addition, when we were checking out, the front desk staff tried to charge us again for the nights we had stayed at the hotel despite us again presenting the pre-paid hotel voucher. It took another 30 minutes to sort this issue out.Overall, I would recommend avoiding this hotel as the level of customer service is sub-standard considering the rates they charge and I would recommend at staying at one of the well-known brands whilst in Beijing (e.g. The Grand Hyatt, Regent Hotel, Peninsulta etc.) as the locally-owned boutique hotels still have a way to go with regards to their understanding of customers.This is a shame as the hotel has a lot of things going for it: cleanliness, excellent location for shopping on Wangfujing and visiting the main sites in Central Beijing (Forbidden city, Tiananmen square, Temple of Heaven etc.). We are both seasoned travellers and this is the first time that I have really been shocked by the standards of service and respect for customers, and will be following up with the management at both Hotelclub.net and Hotel Kapok to re-iterate our concerns about the treatment we were subjected to.	
